		<description><![CDATA[Today a letter to the dutch house of commons (tweede kamer) was sent that informes the representatives about Web 2.0. The letter is found here. (Dutch, but you know how to use Google Translate&#8230;) It gives an insight in laymens terms about the rise of web 2.0 and the empowered position the citizens create for [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Today a letter to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dutch_%28ethnic_group%29" title="Dutch (ethnic group)" rel="wikipedia" class="zem_slink">the dutch</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_of_Commons" title="House of Commons" rel="wikipedia" class="zem_slink">house of commons</a> (tweede kamer) was sent that informes the representatives about <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_2.0" title="Web 2.0" rel="wikipedia" class="zem_slink">Web 2.0</a>. The letter is found <a title="Brief aan de tweede kamer" href="http://www.minbzk.nl/115718/brief-aan-de-tweede_6" target="_blank">here</a>. (<em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Politics_of_the_Netherlands" title="Politics of the Netherlands" rel="wikipedia" class="zem_slink">Dutch</a>, but you know how to use <a title="Google Translate" href="http://translate.google.com/translate_t?hl=nl#nl|en|" target="_blank">Google Translate</a>&#8230;</em>) It gives an insight in laymens terms about the rise of web 2.0 and the empowered position the citizens create for themselves in comparison with the past. Also the letter mentions that many government organisations have been experimenting with several web 2.0 technologies. It goes on to talk about future research and projects in this field.</p>
<p>This is interesting because governments in general aren&#8217;t known to be frontrunners in Technology. Even when many corporations and enterprises are still hardly using any web2.0 services (except for their employees on individual basis) the interest from Government is surely remarkeable.</p>
<p>I personally like these proceedings and think that Web2.0 can aid in the deployment of a true MultiChannel, interactive, transparent and quality-oriented government, while on the other hand using multiple <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_standard" title="Open standard" rel="wikipedia" class="zem_slink">open standards</a> and rather simple technologies to get things done. That&#8217;s in my opinion good for everyone while also making interacting with the Government a lot more fun.</p>
<p>so three cheers from me!  <img src='http://wkossen.nl.nyud.net:8080/weblog/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':-)' class='wp-smiley' /> </p>
<p><a href="http://www.mylivesignature.com" target="_blank"><img src="http://signatures.mylivesignature.com/85709/wkossen/4c685b3de1f98bc3665afa55cc11559d.png" border="0"></a></p>
<div class="zemanta-pixie" style="margin-top:10px;height:15px"><a class="zemanta-pixie-a" href="http://reblog.zemanta.com/zemified/79e3e209-c253-40fb-9cfe-b5764f095957/" title="Zemified by Zemanta"><img class="zemanta-pixie-img" src="http://img.zemanta.com/reblog_e.png?x-id=79e3e209-c253-40fb-9cfe-b5764f095957" alt="Reblog this post [with Zemanta]" style="border:none;float:right"></a></div>
]]></content:encoded>
